WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.080
[Music]

00:00:09.080 --> 00:00:15.160
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger, and this is the&nbsp;
second of a series of videos on the foundations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:21.520
of mathematics. Please have a look at the first&nbsp;
video if you haven't already done so. Last time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:26.160
we introduced the most important objects in&nbsp;
mathematics: the natural numbers. We said that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:32.680
a natural number was just a string of ones, so&nbsp;
the sequence of natural numbers looks just like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:39.440
this: the first one is one, the next one is&nbsp;
1 1, the next one is 1 1 1, and then 1 1 1 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:48.680
and so on. We also mentioned the standard names&nbsp;
for the first few of them: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, but to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:54.920
carry on naming them requires the Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
numeric system, and we don't have that yet. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.920 --> 00:01:01.560
it's safer for us to think of a general number&nbsp;
like this as just 1 1 1 1 1 1, a string of

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:13.120
ones. Alright, so let's go back in time, maybe&nbsp;
100,000 years, to a water hole in Africa. We might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:20.280
imagine a 10-year-old boy there who's been sent&nbsp;
by his tribe to count animals, and he sees a bunch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:28.400
of buffalo and antelope. Let's say buffalo are&nbsp;
these squares and the antelope are the triangles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:33.720
and he's pretty good at counting. He's figured out&nbsp;
a way of counting things. He has a piece of bark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.720 --> 00:01:38.800
and on the bark, he makes little scratches, one&nbsp;
for each of the animals that he sees. So for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:47.560
example, counting buffaloes, here's how he would&nbsp;
do it: there's one, there's one, there's one, one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:56.080
one, one, one, one. Of course, he has to make sure&nbsp;
not to repeat. Counting antelopes is the same:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.080 --> 00:02:09.320
there's one, one, one, one, one, one, one, one,&nbsp;
one. So he goes back to his village with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:15.600
piece of bark, and he shows the elders these&nbsp;
marks, and they can sense how many buffalo&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:21.680
and antelopes there are. They may not have a&nbsp;
name for these numbers like we do, but still,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:27.160
it gives them a very good idea of what's at the&nbsp;
water hole. Now suppose his father asks him,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:33.800
how many animals are there in total? Why don't&nbsp;
you go back and count them all? Our young boy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:38.040
who's rather clever, realizes that he doesn't&nbsp;
have to go back to the water hole to count them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:43.040
all because he has counted the buffalo and he has&nbsp;
counted the antelope, and he can use the numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:51.600
that he has obtained to find the number of all the&nbsp;
animals. He does that by what we call adding those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:59.400
two numbers. How do we do that? Well, he just&nbsp;
copies the first one: one, one, one, one, one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:14.120
one, one, one, and then he adds the second one:&nbsp;
one, one, one, one, one, one, one, one, one, one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:19.160
That then is the total number of animals at the&nbsp;
water hole, and he hasn't had to go back to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:28.880
water hole to do it. He's a very clever young boy.&nbsp;
This is an example of the most important operation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:35.480
in mathematics: the operation of taking the sum&nbsp;
of two numbers. So here's our official definition:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:43.480
the sum of numbers n and m is a combination of the&nbsp;
strings of ones. By combination, I mean you just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:49.240
put them together in the obvious way, concatenate&nbsp;
them in computer science language, and we write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:56.840
that sum as n + m. So our young friend back&nbsp;
in the African savannah 100,000 years ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:03.200
if he kept playing with numbers, let's say he did,&nbsp;
he would probably discover certain facts about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:13.280
this addition operation, and the main facts are&nbsp;
that it's first of all commutative: n + m is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:24.040
same as m + n. Let's illustrate: so here is 5 + 2,&nbsp;
concatenate them, we get this string here. On the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:31.200
other hand, here's 2 + 5, concatenate them, and&nbsp;
these two numbers are the same. We can get that by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:39.840
matching them up one by one. Why is it true? Well,&nbsp;
it's almost obvious. If you combine two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:45.360
it doesn't matter in which order you combine them&nbsp;
if you're just interested in the total number. Or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:50.600
another way of thinking about it is in terms of&nbsp;
inverting them. If we take this pattern here and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:57.160
flip things over, the total number of ones hasn't&nbsp;
changed, but we've gone from that pattern to this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:05.280
pattern. That's the commutative law of addition.&nbsp;
Another main law is the associative law, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:12.560
concerns three numbers. We agree that addition&nbsp;
is an operation that only takes two numbers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:18.640
gives you another number, so if we have three&nbsp;
numbers, there are two possibilities for how to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:25.840
combine them. We can combine k and n first and&nbsp;
then add that to m, or we can take k and add it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:37.360
to the sum of n and m. For example, k is 2, n is&nbsp;
3, m is 4. Here is 2 + 3 + 4, so that's 5 + 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:45.960
giving us this string. On the other hand, 2&nbsp;
+ combination 3 + 4 is 2 + this combination,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:51.400
which gives us this string. And why are these&nbsp;
always the same? If we think of the strings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:57.640
like this, for example, concatenate the first two&nbsp;
and then concatenate with the third, it gives us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:03.200
the same as if we concatenate the second and&nbsp;
third and then concatenate with the first. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:11.040
resulting configuration is the same. A minor law,&nbsp;
which we'll just mention, is that the successor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:21.360
operation, which we talked about last time, can&nbsp;
be rewritten now as n + 1. Those are the laws of

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:31.080
addition. Now things get more complicated when we&nbsp;
introduce multiplication. This is a new level of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:39.760
difficulty. Here's a motivating example: we have&nbsp;
three boxes, say, and in each box, there are four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:47.120
circles. So there are four circles in a box, and&nbsp;
we have altogether three boxes. We'd like to know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:56.840
how many circles are there altogether. Well, it's&nbsp;
a matter of combining 4 + 4 + 4, so we think of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.840 --> 00:07:05.800
this. We're going to write it like this: this is&nbsp;
3 * 4, and that for us means three groups of four.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:12.000
Or a way of thinking about that is we're going&nbsp;
to replace each of the ones in this first string&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:19.520
with a copy of the second number. So that first&nbsp;
one is replaced by a four, the second one here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:25.040
is replaced by another four, and the third one is&nbsp;
replaced by another four to give us this resulting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:32.520
string. So we say that the product of numbers&nbsp;
n and m is the string formed by a copy of m for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:44.760
every one in n. So the laws for multiplication are&nbsp;
these ones: the commutative law, n * m = m * n;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:56.400
the associative law, k * (n * m) = (k * n) *&nbsp;
m. Then there are two additional laws called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:05.360
the distributive laws that connect addition and&nbsp;
multiplication, and they are k * (n + m) is equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:17.520
to k * n + k * m. And we introduce an important&nbsp;
notational device: we say that we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:26.600
allow ourselves to rewrite this expression without&nbsp;
these brackets in the form k * n + k * m. So our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:32.360
convention is that multiplication takes precedence&nbsp;
over addition. In other words, whenever you see a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:37.240
multiplication sign, you have to do that first.&nbsp;
And then there's another distributive law in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:48.960
other direction: (k + n) * m = k * m + n * m. The&nbsp;
laws on these two pages are the most important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:59.320
laws in all of mathematics. In fact, they are far&nbsp;
more important than almost anything else. They're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:05.160
important because they're simple and because their&nbsp;
effect in everyday life is so profound. All of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:14.040
mathematics uses these laws directly or indirectly&nbsp;
all the time. We need to understand why these laws&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:19.360
are true, and we need to understand it in a way&nbsp;
that doesn't involve any abstract symbolism or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:25.440
gobbledygook. We need to be able to explain it in&nbsp;
everyday English using only the notation and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:31.160
conventions that we've established so far. So I'm&nbsp;
going to leave this as an exercise to you for now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:36.360
which we'll talk about in our next video. Right,&nbsp;
but please write out proofs, in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:43.400
reasons for these laws. I've given you reasons&nbsp;
for the addition laws. For the multiplication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:48.200
and distributive laws, see if you can write them&nbsp;
out in a way that our 10-year-old friend in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:53.520
African savannah 100,000 years ago would&nbsp;
understand. Alright, so we'll talk about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:59.160
that in our next video. I'm Norman Wildberger. I&nbsp;
hope you join me. Thanks for listening. [Music]

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:06.680
Let me know if you need any further assistance!

